Description: Phone-as-key PAM authenticator for Linux
 syauth replaces typing a password for PAM-gated actions (sudo,
 login, lockscreen) with an approve-tap on a paired Android phone.
 The phone's signing key is unlocked by a fresh biometric per
 unlock, defeating the NCC link-layer relay class of attacks that
 broke every prior passive BLE PAM module. On phone-absent or
 phone-deny, the module returns PAM_AUTHINFO_UNAVAIL and the
 configured fallback (typically pam_unix) runs, so a dead phone
 never locks the user out.
 .
 The package ships /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/security/pam_syauth.so
 (or the equivalent arm64 multiarch path) plus the `syauth` CLI
 at /usr/bin/syauth. The bond store at /var/lib/syauth/ is created
 with mode 0700 by the postinst hook and is preserved across
 upgrades and uninstalls — to drop a paired phone, run
 `syauth revoke <peer>` before purging the package.
